<h1>Relative Clause</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Splain{{}} @N{{}}
<li> @Vplain{{}} @N{{}}
<li> @Ai{{}} @N{{}}
<li> @Ana{{}} @N{{}}
<li> @N1{{}} @HI{{no}} @N{{}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
Japanese does not have relative pronouns, such as who, that and which. Instead a relative clause precedes a noun to modify it. 
Note that anything which modifies a noun <em>always</em> precedes.
</p>

<p>
The predicate of the sentence which forms the relative clause is in the plain form.
<p>

<p>
The relative clause plus modified noun can be used anywhere in a sentence that a plain noun would be.
</p>

<p>
Particles attached to the noun that acquires a relative clause are deleted.
</p>

<p>
The topic marker @HI{{ha}} does not appear in relative clauses: instead the subject will be marked by either
@HI{{ga}} or @HI{{no}}. However, if the subject of the sentence is followed by a noun and @HI{{no}} then
the meaning of the sentence would not be as intended.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{tomu}}@EM{{ga}} @KT{{futtobo-ru}}no @KJ{{cut^token}}wo ageta @KJ{{woman}}no@KJ{{child}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The girl to whom Tom gave a football ticket.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{tomu}}@EM{{no}} @KT{{futtobo-ru}}no @KJ{{cut^token}}wo ageta @KJ{{woman}}no@KJ{{child}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The girl to whom someone gave Tom's football ticket.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{mira-}}sanga @KJ{{dwell}}nde ita uchihe @KJ{{going}}tta kotoga arimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I have been to the house where Mr. Miller lived.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha @KT{{karina}}sanga kaita @KJ{{picture}}ga @KJ{{fond}}ki desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I like the picture that Ms. Karina drew.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

